@NODE CHAP_ONE "Chapter One: Basics"

@{b}Chapter One: Introduction@{ub}

REDShapeZ (just ShapeZ from now on!) is an extremely powerful tool for game 
designers. There is a huge range of features that have been incorportated 
to help you get the artist's fantastic creations into a form which can be 
used with maximum effciency in the game.

Like any complex piece of software, ShapeZ has some features that are not
always super obvious, so this manual has been designed to try and bring
these out, and help you through. In places we have sacrificed a little
useability in-order to offer you a little more flexibility. Even so, we
have tried to make everything as obvious as possible. We hope we have
succeded in making a product that is very useable, and VERY powerful. 

This chapter will give you a bit of insight to the ideas and motivations
behind ShapeZ. We hope you find this program not only an invaluable part
of the Suite, but an invaluable development tool.

The three main sections of this chapter are:

	@{" 1.1  About ShapeZ" link ABOUT}
	@{" 1.2  Installation" link INSTALL}
	@{" 1.3  Requirements" link REQUIRES}
@ENDNODE CHAP_ONE

@NODE ABOUT "Chapter One: 1.1 About ShapeZ"

@{b}1.1  About ShapeZ@{ub}

ShapeZ came into being for two reasons:

	1) Blitz lacked a really decent shape grabber, and
	2) I wanted a really decent shape grabber.

So it began. After the initial release we began turning ShapeZ into a 
vastly more powerful utility. Initially the ability to edit the shapes 
directly from ShapeZ itself became important, followed by animation tools,
advanced palette manipulation tools, and an AREXX port. With release 2.5 
of ShapeZ (and after noticing ShapeZ went Red When Excited) we hope to 
provide you with a tool that not only supports the Blitz programmer, but
also artists and people who develop code in other (non-Blitz) environments.
Not that we condone developing software in other environments!

ShapeZ is the first Red When Excited development tool to support RED 
Interactive Help, or iRED. iRED supplies you with three different levels
of real-time interactive help, everything form simple prompts to revealing
the inner-most details about what clicking or selecting a button will do.
Consequently, for the impatient amongst you (and if you are a programmer,
you never read the instructions ANYWAY) why not use iRED to get a feel
for what ShapeZ can do, and then learn how to make RED ShapeZ sing and dance
with its powerful functionality and super-useful AREXX port. The Amiga
needs more games, ShapeZ is designed to help you produce them.

@ENDNODE ABOUT

