@NODE CHAP_TWO "Chapter Two: Scanning and Grabbing"

@{b}Chapter Two: Introduction@{ub}

The most fundamental thing that ShapeZ helps you to do is take an image
and extract all of the elements that you want to use as graphical objects
in your game. This can be done in one of two ways, grabbing and scanning.
The former is manual methodology that uses the mouse to allow you to 
specify areas of the image to be grabbed. The later uses a couple of 
techniques to automate this process. There are a couple of drawbacks with
this. Mainly that you have to train your graphic artist to draw his
sprites in a certain way. Ours caught on straight away (well done Mike),
but we all know how difficult artists are! Finally this chapter has a quick
look at how you can jump around the list of shapes in memory (and exactly
WHAT that list is).

The main sections of this chapter are:

	@{" 2.1  Loading in Images" link LOAD_IMAGE}
	@{" 2.2  Grabbing Shapes" link GRABBING}
	@{" 2.3  Scanning Shapes" link SCANNING}
	@{" 2.4  Moving Through The List" link MOVING}

@ENDNODE CHAP_TWO

@NODE LOAD_IMAGE "Chapter Two: 2.1 Loading in Images"

@{b}2.1  Loading in Images@{ub}

Your artist has spent a week drawing a set of beautiful animations to
go into your game. He presents you with a disk crammed full of 256
colour sprites. Wow! You need to "cut" each frame out in order to get
the animations into the game, but before this you need to load the
pictures in. How do you do this? Read on...

@{b}IFF ILBM@{ub}

Firstly you need to know which image formats ShapeZ can interpret. 
Almost all Amiga artpackages can save images in IFF ILBM format. Since
Electronic Arts developed it way back then, it has dominated the Amiga
forum. Unsurprisingly enough, no matter which version of the operating
system you are using, ShapeZ will load all IFF ILBM images. The only
restrictions is that the images must have a fixed palette of between 2 
and 256 colours.

When ShapeZ first runs you will see a single window floating near the 
top of the screen with an array of buttons. One of these has been
helpfully labelled @{b}LOAD IMAGE@{ub}. Click on this button and you
will be presented with a standard file requester. Chose the image you
want to scan, and click on OK. ShapeZ will busy itself loading the
image into memory. When it has, you will be asked a question. ShapeZ
wants to know if it should remove the bottom four colours and set them
to be like the standard Workbench palette. You @{b}must not@{ub} select
OK if you want to scan or grab images. ShapeZ has to remap the image in 
order to do this, and this much up the graphics in the game AND the 
automatic scanning process. It does mean that for some images with very
strange palettes can be loaded, and the gadgets in ShapeZ can be seen.
The requestor defaults to CANCEL, so you can just tap return and the
image will NOT be remapped.

Once you havce answered the question ShapeZ will load the image in,
set the correct screen mode, and display it in the background. That's 
all there is to it! You are now ready to @{"Grab" link GRABBING} or @{"Scan" link SCANNING} your shapes.

@{b}Datatype Support@{ub}

From version 3 of Workbench, Commodore added Datatypes. These are great 
little bits of code that allow applications like ShapeZ to load in 
images and sounds that they do not explicitly know how to interpret.

If your Amiga is running Workbench 3.0 or above, ShapeZ will use
your datatypes to try and load image that it does not recognise
the format of. There are tens of datatypes available, supporting
@{b}JPEG, GIF, TARGA, PCX, BMP,@{ub} and many more. We have
experienced some problems with some datatypes causing ShapeZ to crash.
With most data-types we have no problems, and we have always been
able to find an alternative to any problem-datatypes. We are not 
certain whether this is due to a problem with how we handle datatypes,
or a problem with the datatypes themselves. 

@ENDNODE LOAD_IMAGE

@NODE GRABBING "Chapter Two: 2.2 Grabbing Shapes"

@{b}2.1  Grabbing Shapes@{ub}

Once you have loaded your image, you can start grabbing shapes from 
it. Click on the @{b}GRAB@{ub} gadget, and the control window will 
disappear, leaving two glowing line intersecting at your mouse
pointer. You have probably had to drag a box around something before,
but let's go through it anyway. 

	1) Press and hold the mouse button when you are pointing to
	the top-left hand corner of the shape you wish to cut out.

	2) Drag the mouse down to the bottom right of the shape, you should
	now have the shape surrounded by a glowing box. 

	3) Release the mouse button. 

After ShapeZ has grabbed a shape it will flash the screen to let you
know that the shape has been grabbed OK. You can cut out as many
shapes as you like now, just keep repeating the above procedure 
for each shape.

To return to the main part of ShapeZ, click the right mouse button once,
the control window will re-appear! You should now see a counter at the 
bottom of the control window, it will say something like, 

	Shape 1 of 10

This lets you know which shape you are currently "editting". Normally
grabbed shapes are added to the end of the list, but by clicking
on the @{b}INSERT@{ub} check box at the bottom of the control window, 
you can set them to be inserted after the current shape. 

All you need to do now is save your shapes, you can read all about that in
@{"Chapter Four" link CHAP_FOUR}.
@ENDNODE GRABBING

@NODE SCANNING "Chapter Two: 2.1 Scanning Shapes"

@{b}2.1  Scanning Shapes@{ub}

Scanning performs the tedious process of cutting out shapes from the image
automatically. The price of this speed-up is that ShapeZ needs some kind
of hint as to what to cut out. ShapeZ supports two types of scanning,
@{b}ShapeZ Scan@{ub} and @{b}Acid Scan@{ub}. They both require some kind
of border to be drawn around the shape. There are examples of the kind of
border that needs to be drawn in the Examples/Images directory. First of
all let's look at how each scanning method works.

@{b}ShapeZ Scan@{ub}

Of the two techniques, ShapeZ scan is the fastest. Its requirements are 
very simple. A border has to be drawn around the shape in a single 
colour. Which colour this is can be set in the general page of the 
configuration window. It will default to colour one. There is @{b}nothing@{ub}
to stop you using that colour within the shapes, ShapeZ just uses the box 
to work out what it should cut out, it never looks inside the box. 

It is this scanning mode which is the @{b}default@{ub} when you click on
Scan from the control window. If you are scanning a big image with 
hundreds of shapes on, it can take a long time. ShapeZ has some options
to either speed things up, or sacrifice a little speed so that it can
let you know what is going on. From the configuration page you can
set the @{b}Scan Info@{ub} level to one of three settings, 

	1) Off  - No visual feedback, it is complete when the control window
	reappears. This is the fastest mode.

	2) Mid  - A Progress bar telling you how far through the image it is.

	3) Full - As well as the progress bar, shapes are removed from the 
	image as they are cut out. This is the slowest mode.

It is @{b}recommended@{ub} that this is the scanning mode you should use. Not
only is it faster, but its behaviour is more predicatble than the acid scan. 

@{b}Acid Scan@{ub}

The acid scan operates in the same way as ShapeZ Scan except that it simply
looks for a colour that is not zero, then scans right until it finds another
colour zero pixel, scans down until it finds another colour zero pixel. This
means that your box must be part of the shape. The line will be removed, 
but my artist finds this a little too obtrusive. The reason for its inclusion
is that many people used the original Acid Scanner, and they still need to
edit those shapes. You should move over to ShapeZ scan as soon as possible.
To convert an image from acid format to ShapeZ format, load it in, Acid Scan
it, and save it as IFF (see @{"4.1.3" link ILBF}). ShapeZ saves out in a 
format that it can rescan with ShapeZ scan.

In order to trigger an Acid Scan, you must pick from the Scan sub-menu of the
Project Menu. That's it below ShapeZ scan.

For a demonstration of scanning, please run ShapeZ and click @{"here" SYSTEM "Blitz2:REDHelp/REDShapeZ/tutorials 0"}

@ENDNODE SCANNING

@NODE MOVING "Chapter Two: 2.1 Moving Through The List"

@{b}2.1  Moving Through The List@{ub}

Once you have or grabbed your shapes, you will probably want to zip through
them, check each one out and edit them in some way. First off open a 
@{b}View Window@{ub}. You do this be checking the View click box on the
control panel. If you have some shapes in memory this will appear displaying
the current shape. You can move through the shapes list in 3 ways:

	1) Selecting 	First (go to first shape in list)
			Last  (go to last shape in list)
			Next  (go to next shape in list)
			Prev  (go to previous shape in list)

	   from the @{b}Shape Menu@{ub}.
	2) Using the @{"keyboard shortcuts" link SHORTCUTS} assigned to these items
	
	3) Using the buttons in the @{"Editor" link EDITOR} window.

If you have the viewing window open, the current shape will be displayed in there
and will update automatically.

@ENDNODE MOVING

@NODE CHAP_THREE "Chapter 3: Cut, Paste, Tweek and Fiddle"

